{{Infobox book | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] --> | name = In An Antique Land | title_orig = | translator = | image = In an Antique Land.jpg| caption = | author = [[Amitav Ghosh]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = India | language = [[English language|English]] | series = | genre = [[Non-fiction]] | publisher = Ravi Dayal Publishers | pub_date = 1992 | english_pub_date = | media_type = Print ([[Hardcover|hardback]]) | pages = | isbn = 0679727833 | preceded_by = | followed_by = [[Dancing in Cambodia and at Large in Burma]] }}
'''''In An Antique Land''''' is an [[ethnography]] written in [[Narrative|narrative form]] by the Indian writer [[Amitav Ghosh]].
==Summary== The book contains two narratives. The first, an anthropological narrative, revolves around two visits made by Ghosh to two villages in the [[Nile Delta]], while he was writing his doctoral dissertation (1980–81) and again a few years later (1988). In the second narrative, presented parallel to the first one in the book, Ghosh reconstructs the history of a 12th-century Jewish merchant, Abraham Ben Yiju, and his slaves Ashu and Bomma, using documents from the [[Cairo Geniza]].<ref name=desai>{{Cite journal|title=Old World Orders: Amitav Ghosh and the Writing of Nostalgia|last=Desai|first=Gaurav|journal=Representations|volume=85|issue=Winter 2004|publisher=California University Press|pages=125–148|jstor=10}}</ref>
==Commentary== ''In an Antique Land'' is considered to be a stylistically curious book. Written after the success of Ghosh's first two books, ''[[The Circle of Reason (novel)|The Circle of Reason]]'' and ''[[The Shadow Lines]]'', and written more than a decade after the dissertation on which the book is based, In an Antique Land defies easy description and has been called "generically indefinable" and could be labelled as "narrative, travel book, autobiographical piece, historical account".<ref name=srivastava>{{Cite journal|title=Amitav Ghosh’s Ethnographic Fictions: Intertextual Links between In An Antique Land and His Doctoral Thesis|last=Srivastava|first=Neelam|volume=36|issue=June 2001|publisher=Sage Publications|journal=The Journal of Commonwealth Literature|accessdate=11 April 2011|pages=45–64|url=http://jcl.sagepub.com/content/36/2/45.full.pdf|doi=10.1177/002198940103600205}}</ref>
